<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/22957412-mark-naylor"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1376052150i/22957412._UX100_CR0,0,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/22957412-mark-naylor">Mark Naylor</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<span class="expandableContainer"><span class="truncatedContent">I would skip the whole series. I put up with &quot;Christianity Is Wrong&quot; for 𝘛𝘩𝘦 𝘛𝘦𝘮𝘱𝘭𝘢𝘳 𝘓𝘦𝘨𝘢𝘤𝘺 hoping it was a quirk, but partway into 𝘛𝘩𝘦 𝘈𝘭𝘦𝘹𝘢𝘯𝘥𝘳𝘪𝘢 𝘓𝘪𝘯<a class="jsShow showAction" href="#">…more</a></span><span class="fullContent">I would skip the whole series. I put up with "Christianity Is Wrong" for 𝘛𝘩𝘦 𝘛𝘦𝘮𝘱𝘭𝘢𝘳 𝘓𝘦𝘨𝘢𝘤𝘺 hoping it was a quirk, but partway into 𝘛𝘩𝘦 𝘈𝘭𝘦𝘹𝘢𝘯𝘥𝘳𝘪𝘢 𝘓𝘪𝘯𝘬 I saw that it was becoming a theme.<br /><br />Fortunately I did not waste any money; I had borrowed the first two from my local library. I returned the second book only having read about 15%-20% and canceled the holds I had one books three and four.<br /><br />A shame, because I read his four standalone books and liked them. Similar to Clive Cussler with modern people searching for treasures from the historic past. And, not a hint of anti-Bible bigotry.<a class="jsHide hideAction" href="#">(less)</a></span></span>
</span>
</div>
